\title{pft: Pulmonary Function Test Interpretation per ERS/ATS 2022}
\description{
\code{pft} implements the Stanojevic 2022 ERS/ATS interpretive standard
for pulmonary function tests. Reference values come from the GLI
family of equations (GLI 2012 and GLI Global 2022 spirometry,
GLI 2021 static lung volumes, GLI 2017 TLCO with the 2020 author
correction). On top of those, the package computes z-scores and
percent predicted, severity grading, ATS pattern classification,
bronchodilator response per the 2022 criterion, PRISm screening,
conditional change scores for serial measurements, GOLD COPD
severity grading, Graham 2019 spirometry quality grades, and a
ggplot2-based clinical lollipop figure.
}
\section{Input data format}{

Every reference function (\code{pft_spirometry()}, \code{pft_volumes()},
\code{pft_diffusion()}, \code{pft_interpret()}) reads from canonical column
names (\code{sex}, \code{age}, \code{height}, and -- for GLI 2012 -- \code{race}) by
default. If your data frame names them differently, point at them
explicitly via tidyverse-style column references:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{pft_spirometry(d, sex = Sex, age = Age_y,
                  height = Ht_cm, race = Ancestry)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Bare names, strings (\code{sex = "Sex"}), and rlang injection
(\code{sex = !!my_var}) are all accepted. The user's original column
names are preserved in the output.

Optional \verb{<measure>_measured}, \verb{<measure>_pre}, and
\verb{<measure>_post} columns unlock z-score, percent-predicted, and
bronchodilator-response outputs respectively; these are looked up
by literal name (not overridable). See \code{vignette("input-format")}
for a walkthrough.
}

\section{Conventions used throughout}{

To support unambiguous clinical and research use, the following
conventions hold across every exported function:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Sex} is canonically coded as the character string \code{"M"} or
\code{"F"}. Common variants (\code{"male"}, \code{"Female"}, \code{"m"}, \code{"woman"},
etc.) are auto-normalised with a warning. Truly unrecognised
values (\code{"X"}, \code{"Unknown"}, etc.) are treated as missing.
\item \strong{Age} is in years (decimal allowed).
\item \strong{Height} is in centimetres.
\item \strong{Volumes} (FEV1, FVC, FRC, TLC, RV, ERV, IC, VC) are in litres.
\item \strong{DLCO / TLCO} are reported in the units the function emits
(controlled by \code{SI.units} in \code{\link[=pft_diffusion]{pft_diffusion()}}).
\item \strong{z-scores} use the LMS-based formula
\code{z = ((measured / M)^L - 1) / (L * S)} and are SIGNED such that
values below 0 are below the predicted median.
\item \strong{Lower limit of normal (LLN)} is the 5th percentile of the
reference distribution; \strong{upper limit of normal (ULN)} is the
95th percentile. Both correspond to z-scores of -1.645 and +1.645
respectively.
\item \strong{NA handling}: rows missing \code{sex}, \code{age}, or \code{height} get all-NA
outputs. The same applies for \code{race} in the GLI 2012 path. Other
NA inputs propagate naturally through arithmetic.
\item \strong{The 4-character pattern combination} emitted by \code{\link[=pft_classify]{pft_classify()}}
uses positions FEV1, FVC, FEV1/FVC, TLC, in that order, with
\code{"A"} denoting below the LLN and \code{"N"} denoting at or above. So
\code{"NNAN"} means only FEV1/FVC is below its LLN.
}
}

\section{Implemented reference standards}{

\itemize{
\item \strong{Spirometry, GLI 2012}: Quanjer et al. \emph{Eur Respir J} 2012;40(6):1324-43.
\doi{10.1183/09031936.00080312}.
\item \strong{Spirometry, GLI Global 2022}: Bowerman et al. \emph{Am J Respir Crit Care Med}
2023;207(6):768-74. \doi{10.1164/rccm.202205-0963OC}.
\item \strong{Static lung volumes, GLI 2021}: Hall et al. \emph{Eur Respir J}
2021;57(3):2000289. \doi{10.1183/13993003.00289-2020}.
\item \strong{Carbon-monoxide transfer factor, GLI 2017}: Stanojevic et al.
\emph{Eur Respir J} 2017;50(3):1700010. \doi{10.1183/13993003.00010-2017}.
The 2020 author correction (\doi{10.1183/13993003.50010-2017}) is
the version implemented.
\item \strong{Spirometry acquisition standard 2019}: Graham et al.
\emph{Am J Respir Crit Care Med} 2019;200(8):e70-e88.
\doi{10.1164/rccm.201908-1590ST}. Implemented by \code{\link[=pft_quality]{pft_quality()}}.
\item \strong{Interpretive strategy 2022}: Stanojevic et al. \emph{Eur Respir J}
2022;60(1):2101499. \doi{10.1183/13993003.01499-2021}. Implemented
by \code{\link[=pft_classify]{pft_classify()}}, \code{\link[=pft_severity]{pft_severity()}}, \code{\link[=pft_bdr]{pft_bdr()}}, \code{\link[=pft_prism]{pft_prism()}},
\code{\link[=pft_change]{pft_change()}}, and \code{\link[=pft_interpret]{pft_interpret()}}.
\item \strong{COPD severity}: Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung
Disease (GOLD). \url{https://goldcopd.org}. Implemented by
\code{\link[=pft_gold]{pft_gold()}}.
\item \strong{Predecessor interpretive strategy 2005}: Pellegrino et al.
\emph{Eur Respir J} 2005;26(5):948-68.
\doi{10.1183/09031936.05.00035205}. Cited for historical comparison
in \code{\link[=pft_classify]{pft_classify()}}.
}
}

\section{Scope and limitations}{

\code{pft} does \strong{not} currently cover:
\itemize{
\item Reference equations outside the GLI family (NHANES III, JRS,
ECSC, Knudson, Crapo, Hankinson, etc.). Use the rspiro package for
NHANES III and JRS.
\item Ethnic groups outside the five recognised by GLI 2012 (Caucasian,
African American, North-East Asian, South-East Asian, Other/mixed).
The GLI Global 2022 equations are race-neutral and apply across
ancestral groups.
\item Pre-school spirometry (ages < 3).
\item Bronchial challenge testing (PC20 methacholine, mannitol).
\item Cardiopulmonary exercise testing.
\item Six-minute walk test interpretation.
\item Sleep-study integration.
\item Pediatric-specific bronchodilator-response thresholds (the 2022
adult criterion is applied uniformly).
\item Sub-patterns within the Stanojevic 2022 algorithm that the
coarse 5-category classifier doesn't enumerate (Dysanapsis, etc.).
The package's \code{\link[=pft_classify]{pft_classify()}} folds Dysanapsis into "Obstructed"
when FEV1/FVC is below its LLN.
\item Altitude corrections to DLCO. (Haemoglobin correction \emph{is}
supported -- see \code{\link[=pft_dlco_hb_correct]{pft_dlco_hb_correct()}}.)
\item Sex categories outside \code{"M"} and \code{"F"}.
}

Outputs are intended for research and education. Clinical decisions
should be made by qualified clinicians using validated tools; \code{pft}
is not FDA-cleared, not a medical device, and not validated for
diagnostic decision-making.
}

\section{Reproducibility}{

Every internal reference-equation coefficient and spline-table value
in \code{R/sysdata.rda} is reproducibly built from the corresponding
official ERS / AJRCCM source document via the scripts in
\code{data-raw/build_gli_*.R}. The source PDFs and supplement workbooks
are not redistributed with the package (they are copyrighted
publisher content); the build scripts document where to obtain them.
}

